Definition: A description of the events and procedures that take place under the purview of an organized activity, such as a co-curricular or extra-curricular activity that is offered at an education institution.

ElementName: Recognition for Participation or Performance in an Activity
Definition: The nature of recognition given to the student for accomplishments in a co-curricular, or extra-curricular activity.
The level of work which is reflected in the credits associated with the academic course being described or the level of the typical individual taking the academic course.
The career cluster that defines the industry or occupational focus which may be associated with a career pathways program, plan of study, or course.
UsageNotes: Options from O*NET OnLine an application that was created for the general public to provide broad access to the O*NET database of occupational information. O*NET OnLine offers a variety of search options and occupational data, while My Next Move is a streamlined application for students and job seekers. Both applications were developed for the U.S. Department of Labor by the National Center for O*NET Development.  See onetonline.org for more information.
ChangeNotes: Added elements to DES contexts to support post-secondary needs

Definition: A classification of whether a postsecondary institution's highest level of offering is a program of 4-years or higher (4 year), 2-but-less-than 4-years (2 year), or less than 2-years.

ElementName: Years of Prior Adult Education Teaching Experience
Definition: The total number of years that a person has previously held a teaching position in one or more adult education programs.
Format: Numeric - up to 2 digits after decimal place
ChangeNotes: Added elements to DES contexts to support post-secondary needs

Definition: The titles of employment, official status, or rank of adult education staff.
The condition under which a person has agreed to serve as an employee.
The month and year on which the diploma/credential is awarded to a student in recognition of his/her completion of the curricular requirements.
The type of diploma/credential that is awarded to a person in recognition of his/her completion of the curricular requirements.
UsageNotes: Use "Other Diploma" instead of "Other" option.

Definition: An indicator of the category of credential conferred by a state occupational licensing entity or industry organization for competency in a specific area measured by a set of pre-established standards.
The North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) code associated with an individual's employment.

An individual who is a paid employee or works in his or her own business, profession, or farm, as reported through the State Unemployment Insurance Wage Report, FEDES, or WRIS, and at the same time is enrolled in secondary, postsecondary, or adult education or workforce programs.
UsageNotes: Individual-level data obtained by matching records with wage records, FEDES, or WRIS. The State Education Agency defines the time period for this collection around an exit period and a corresponding period for employment and earnings data to be obtained. The option set includes "Yes" for employment found via one of the resources listed in the source element. These sources won't tell you anything further about employment or unemployment, only that a record was "not found" or "not matched" thus "unknown."

Definition: An individual who is a paid employee or works in his or her own business, profession, or farm, as reported through the State Unemployment Insurance Wage Report, FEDES, or WRIS, after exiting secondary, postsecondary, or adult education or workforce programs.
UsageNotes: Individual-level data obtained by matching records with wage records, FEDES, or WRIS. The State Education Agency defines the time period for this collection around an exit period and a corresponding period for employment and earnings data to be obtained. The option set includes "Yes" for employment found via one of the resources listed in the source element. These sources will provide information about most of the types of jobs that students or former students will  become employed in but not all.  For that reason when a record is "not found" or "not matched" their employment status is "unknown" for the targeted time base.

ElementName: Assessment Item Body Custom Interaction XML
Definition: The custom interaction provides an opportunity for extensibility of this specification to include support for interactions not currently documented.  The XML from the IMS Global APIP Specification would be included.
The position of this APIP Interaction in a sequence of interactions.

ElementName: Assessment Item Body Drawing Interaction XML
Definition: The drawing interaction allows the candidate to use a common set of drawing tools to modify a given graphical image (the canvas). It must be bound to a response variable with base-type file and single cardinality. The result is a file in the same format as the original image. The XML from the IMS Global APIP Specification would be included.
The name of a data system or application which an authenticated person may access.
The Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) of a data system or application which an authenticated person may access.
A unique number or alphanumeric code assigned to an assessment by a school, school system, a state, or other agency or entity.  This may be the publisher identifier.
UsageNotes: CEDS "Identifier" elements reflect the intent of the XSD:Token format, i.e. a string in which carriage return, line feed, and tab characters have been removed as well as any internal sequences of two or more spaces and any leading or trailing spaces. <br/><br/>An Identifier MAY be a Universally Unique Identifier (UUID) / Globally Unique Identifier (GUID), i.e.128-bit unique identifiers generated according to the algorithms and encoding standards of RFC 4122.

Definition: A coding scheme that is used for identification and record-keeping purposes by schools, social services, or other agencies to refer to an assessment.
The globally unique identifier of an Assessment using a RFC 4122 compliant hexadecimal string.
UsageNotes: CEDS "GUID" elements are defined as RFC 4122 compliant 32-character hexadecimal strings (36 characters with dashes). For example, 21EC2020-3AEA-1069-A2DD-08002B30309D. <br/><br/>Values MAY be encoded using a hash function such as HMAC-MD5 or HMAC-SHA1, resulting in a string up to 40 characters.

Definition: The title or name of the assessment.
An abbreviated title for an assessment.
The description of the academic content or subject area (e.g., arts, mathematics, reading, or a foreign language) being evaluated.
This is the objective that the assessment is measuring.
Identifies the provider or publisher of the assessment.
UsageNotes: AIF property

Definition: The reason for which an assessment is designed or delivered.
UsageNotes: This element might have multiple occurrences associated with any one assessment.

Definition: The category of an assessment based on format and content.

ElementName: Assessment Type Administered to Children with Disabilities
Definition: The types of assessments administered to children with disabilities.
The month, day, and year that the conceptual design for the assessment was most recently revised substantially.

The full title of the Assessment Family. An Assessment Family is a set of assessments with a common name, jurisdiction, or focus, such as Graduate Record Exam or National Assessment of Educational Progress.
The abbreviated title of the Assessment Family. An Assessment Family is a set of assessments with a common name, jurisdiction, or focus.
UsageNotes: Examples: SAT, GRE, NAEP

Definition: The description of the accommodation when 'Accommodation Type' is set to 'Other'.
The specific accommodation necessary for assessment or instruction.
A category of accommodations needed for a given assessment.
The start date of the time period designated for the assessment administration.
The start time of the time period designated for the assessment administration.
The finish date of the time period designated for the assessment administration.
The finish time of the time period designated for the assessment administration.
Indicates whether or not the assessment is a secure assessment.
The period or window in which an assessment is supposed to be administered.
A version number or label defined by the publisher.
UsageNotes: In some use cases a date, such as Learning Resource Date Created may be used as an alternative to a version number.  Each use case may adopt different rules depending on the application requirements for maintenance of current version only or the multiple objects/records representing the complete version history.

Definition: The date that this version of the asset was made available for use.
The type of identifier that is provided for this asset.

Specifies a predominant type of assessment asset represented by the Learning Resource.  Assessment assets represent any content used to compose an assessment item, is referenced by an item but not part of the item content itself, or is content that is included as part of a section within an assessment form. Assets can be static content such as art work or dynamic assets such as calculators.
UsageNotes: The standard option set may be extended based on local and implementation-specific requirements.  Commonly used options may be submitted for inclusion in future versions of CEDS.

Definition: The name of the ownership rights holder or publisher of the asset.
The language in which the assessment form is designed to be delivered.
UsageNotes: The CEDS ISO 639-2 Language Code option set comes from the <a href="http://www.loc.gov/standards/iso639-2/langhome.html">ISO 639-2 standard</a>, the character encoding in ISO 8859-1 download.  Discontinued codes from the ISO standard are not included in the CEDS list.

Definition: XML encoded in UTF-8 representing the content of the Assessment Asset.
MIME type to specifically indicate the Assessment Asset content type.
The Uniform Resource Locator (URL) location of the external Assessment Asset content.
The number of a given assessment form.
The human readable list of one or more of the specific accommodations available. If no accommodations are provided, then this list will not be present.
The beginning date of the time period in which the form is intended to be administered.

ElementName: Assessment Form Intended Administration End Date
Definition: The ending date of the time period in which the assessment form is intended to be administered.
UsageNotes: All CEDS Exit and End Dates represent the last day of the date range specified, such as the last day that a person was enrolled, participated, or received services.

Definition: If the assessment is provided with an item bank, then this identifies the item bank: a unique code or number used by the item banking system.
UsageNotes: CEDS "Identifier" elements reflect the intent of the XSD:Token format, i.e. a string in which carriage return, line feed, and tab characters have been removed as well as any internal sequences of two or more spaces and any leading or trailing spaces. <br/><br/>An Identifier MAY be a Universally Unique Identifier (UUID) / Globally Unique Identifier (GUID), i.e.128-bit unique identifiers generated according to the algorithms and encoding standards of RFC 4122.

Definition: If the assessment is provided with an item bank, then this is the name of the item bank.
A human readable list of delivery platforms the form will support.
Indicates that the assessment form was generated using an algorithm rather than a fixed form.
An identifier for algorithm used to generate a custom form for an adaptive test.
UsageNotes: The algorithm is typically used to generate the entire assessment form, but there may be cases in which it is used to generate only one part (Assessment Form Section).<br/><br/>CEDS "Identifier" elements reflect the intent of the XSD:Token format, i.e. a string in which carriage return, line feed, and tab characters have been removed as well as any internal sequences of two or more spaces and any leading or trailing spaces. <br/><br/> An Identifier MAY be a Universally Unique Identifier (UUID) / Globally Unique Identifier (GUID), i.e.128-bit unique identifiers generated according to the algorithms and encoding standards of RFC 4122.

Definition: The version of the algorithm used to generate a custom form for an adaptive test.
UsageNotes: The algorithm is typically used to generate the entire assessment form, but there may be cases in which it is used to generate only one part (Assessment Form Section).

Definition: The globally unique identifier of an Assessment Form.
UsageNotes: CEDS "GUID" elements are defined as RFC 4122 compliant 32-character hexadecimal strings (36 characters with dashes). For example, 21EC2020-3AEA-1069-A2DD-08002B30309D. <br/><br/>Values MAY be encoded using a hash function such as HMAC-MD5 or HMAC-SHA1, resulting in a string up to 40 characters.

ElementName: Identification System for Assessment Form Section
Definition: A coding scheme that is used for identification of an Assessment Form Section.
If this section is timed, then this will identify the maximum amount of time the test taker can spend within this section.
Indicates this section is sealed, meaning the test taker cannot enter the section until authorized by the proctor.

Indicates that this section can be re-entered, meaning the test taker can return to this section after they have left the section. A common example of this is a two section test where one section does not allow the use of a calculator and the other does. Typically the test taker cannot return to the non-calculator section after they have used a calculator.
The specific type of assessment item.
The complete text of an assessment item including all applicable parts such as stimulus, stem, and possible response options presented.
The text, source (e.g., video clip), and/or graphic about which the assessment item is written. The stimulus provides the context of the item/task to which the student must respond.
The statement of the question or prompt for an Assessment Item to which the student responds.
This indicator determines whether an assessment item is an adaptive item.
The maximum number of points possible for the assessment item.
The minimum number of points possible for the assessment item.
The analysis of the distractors provided for a specific assessment.
The amount of time allotted for a specific item.
Complexity levels defined by the National Assessment of Educational Progress (NAEP 2005a Framework).
Aspects of reading defined by the National Assessment of Educational Progress (NAEP 2005b Framework).
The percentage of students who answered the item correctly during trial testing of the item.
Format: Numeric - up to 3 digits before and 2 digits after decimal place

Definition: The scaling system used to specify the text complexity of an assessment item.
The complexity of the text using the scaling system defined by Text Complexity System, e.g. LexileT for assessment items with a reading passage.
Indicates that the item is intended to be administered in two different grades for the goal of establishing cross grade comparison.
Indicates that the assessment item has been released to the public.

ElementName: Assessment Form Section Item Field Test Indicator
Definition: Indicates that the assessment item is being field tested on this form of the test, and is not to be included for scoring.

ElementName: Assessment Item APIP Response Processing Template URL
Definition: These templates are described using the processing language defined in IMS Global APIP specification and are distributed (in XML form) along with it. Delivery engines that support generalized response processing do not need to implement special mechanisms to support them as a template file can be parsed directly while processing the assessment item that refers to it. This element provides the URL for the template.

ElementName: Assessment Item APIP Response Processing XML
Definition: Response processing is the process by which the Delivery Engine assigns outcomes based on the learner's responses. The outcomes may be used to provide feedback to the learner Feedback is either provided immediately following the end of the learner's attempt or it is provided at some later time, perhaps as part of a summary report on the item session. The XML from the IMS Global APIP Specification would be included.

ElementName: Assessment Item APIP Response Declaration XML
Definition: Response declarations state what the response variables include.  The response declaration may assign an optional correct response. The XML from the IMS Global APIP Specification would be included.

ElementName: Assessment Item APIP Outcome Declaration XML
Definition: Outcome variables are declared by outcome declarations. Their value is set either from a default given in the declaration itself or by a responseRule during response processing.  The XML from the IMS Global APIP Specification would be included.

ElementName: Assessment Item APIP Template Declaration XML
Definition: Template declarations declare item variables that are to be used specifically for the purposes of cloning items. They can have their value set only during template processing. They are referred to within the item body in order to individualize the clone and possibly also within the response Processing rules if the cloning process affects the way the item is scored.  The XML from the IMS Global APIP Specification would be included.

ElementName: Assessment Item APIP Template Processing XML
Definition: Template processing consists of one or more template rules that are followed by the cloning engine or delivery system in order to assign values to the template variables. Template processing is identical in form to responseProcessing except that the purpose is to assign values to template variables, not outcome variables. The XML from the IMS Global APIP Specification would be included.

ElementName: Assessment Item APIP Modal Feedback XML
Definition: Modal feedback is shown to the candidate directly following response processing. The value of an outcome variable is used in conjunction with the showHide and identifier attributes to determine whether or not the feedback is shown in a similar way to feedbackElement. The XML from the IMS Global APIP Specification would be included.

ElementName: Assessment Item APIP Item Body XML
Definition: The item body contains the text, graphics, media objects, and interactions that describe the item's content and information about how it is structured. The body is presented by combining it with stylesheet information, either explicitly or implicitly using the default style rules of the delivery or authoring system. This element contains the appropriate XML from the IMS Global APIP Specification defining the various item body interactions.
The type of psychometric measure provided for assessment item.
A psychometric measure provided for an assessment item.
The distribution of responses for each choice in the assessment item.
The possible response presented to the participant within a selected-response/multiple-choice assessment item.

ElementName: Assessment Item Possible Response Correct Indicator
Definition: Indicates that the possible response is the correct response.

ElementName: Assessment Item Possible Response Feedback Message
Definition: A message provided to the person being assessed after giving a response that matches the possible response.
UsageNotes: This may be a message of affirmation for a correct answer or descriptive feedback for an incorrect answer.  For example, if the item asked the question what is 2 times 3 and the learner answered 5, the Feedback Message might be "Try multiplication instead of addition."

Definition: The score given to a person's response to an assessment item.
The status of the response for a given item.
An indication of whether a student's scores were proficient.

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Aid Set Used
Definition: A tool or aid set used while viewing the item. This can include things like a calculator, reference tools, etc.
UsageNotes: This a permissible set of tools suggested for use for successful completion of a test question, not an accommodation.

Definition: The formative descriptive feedback that was given to a learner in response to the results from a scored/evaluated assessment item.

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Scaffolding Item Flag
Definition: Indicates that the response is to a scaffolding problem rather than the main/assigned problem.  A scaffolding item is a follow-up formative assessment item used to assess prerequisite or component skills, presented immediately after a learner gives an incorrect answer on the previous item.

The total number of hints presented as the learner responded to a formative assessment item.  This may include hints requested by the learner or hints automatically presented such as in an online tutoring system. Presentation of a scaffolding item is a separate response record and not counted as a hint.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Hint Included Answer
Definition: Indicates that one of the hints presented included the correct answer.
UsageNotes: A typical scenario for an online tutoring application may present a series of hints for a formative assessment item with the last hint being the correct answer.  The learner must enter the correct answer before continuing.  This data element is a flag that the learner was presented with the "bottom hint", which is the correct answer.

Definition: The total amount of time in seconds or milliseconds  that a person spent responding to a given assessment item.

ElementName: Assessment Item Response First Attempt Duration
Definition: The amount of time in seconds or milliseconds that a person took to give an initial response, a first attempt to answer a formative assessment item.
UsageNotes: Formative assessments often allow learners to make multiple attempts until a correct or acceptable answer is given.  In such cases it is valuable to know both the time it took for the initial response and the total time spent responding to the problem.

Definition: The description of security issue, if any, related to a learner's response to an assessment item.
UsageNotes: For example: Suspected plagiarism ; Computer left test window ; Excessive response time ; Proctor suspected copying ; Student identity not confirmed ; No proctor present ; Student carried wireless mobile device during test ; Student terminated test early and restarted ; Excessive erasures on test form ; Response pattern identical to another student's

Definition: The  assessment item result formatted according to the IMS Global QTI  Specification.
UsageNotes: See http://www.imsglobal.org/question/qtiv2p1/imsqti_resultv2p1.html#element10818

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Descriptive Feedback Date
Definition: The date and time the descriptive feedback was entered in response to the results from a scored/evaluated assessment item.
The status of scoring a person's response to an assessment item.

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Theory Parameter A
Definition: The Item Response Theory value representing the discrimination of the item. The a parameter is found by taking the slope of the line tangent to the item characteristic curve at the inflection point, B. The parameter is the steepness of the curve at its steepest point.

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Theory Parameter B
Definition: The Item Response Theory value representing the difficulty of the item.   It is the Theta value for the location of the inflection point of the item characteristic curve.

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Theory Parameter C
Definition: The Item Response Theory value for multiple choice items representing the guessing of the item. The c parameter is a lower asymptote. It is the low point of the curve as it moves to negative infinity on the horizontal axis. You can think of c as the probability that a chicken would get the item right.

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Theory Parameter D1
Definition: For   polytomous assessment items with more than two possible responses, this is the item response theory value representing the threshold between the first and second item characteristic functions.

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Theory Parameter D2
Definition: For   polytomous assessment items with more than two possible responses, this is the item response theory value representing the threshold between the second and third item characteristic functions.

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Theory Parameter D3
Definition: For   polytomous assessment items with more than three possible responses, this is the item response theory value representing the threshold between the third and fourth item characteristic functions.

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Theory Parameter D4
Definition: For   polytomous assessment items with more than four possible responses, this is the item response theory value representing the threshold between the fourth and fifth item characteristic functions.

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Theory Parameter D5
Definition: For   polytomous assessment items with more than five possible responses, this is the item response theory value representing the threshold between the fifth and sixth item characteristic functions.

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Theory Parameter D6
Definition: For   polytomous assessment items with more than six possible responses, this is the item response theory value representing the threshold between the sixth and seventh item characteristic functions.

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Theory Point Biserial Correlation Value
Definition: The correlation between correct answers on this item and total correct answers on the test during a previous administration.�

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Theory DIF Value
Definition: A value representing the Differential Item Functioning, also referred to as  measurement bias, for the assessment item.  The value represents differences in the functioning of the item across groups which are matched on the attribute being measure by the item.  The value is calculated using Mantel-Haenszel approach or a comparable algorithm so that a value of 1.0 represents no bias.

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Theory Kappa Value
Definition: The measure used to represent the degree of agreement among raters.

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Theory Parameter Difficulty Category
Definition: A category for the difficulty of the item based on the Item Response Theory value.

ElementName: Assessment Item Response Theory Kappa Algorithm
Definition: The algorithm used to derive the Assessment Item Kappa Value

ElementName: Assessment Need Item Translation Display Language Type
Definition: Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the default language for the displayed translation.
UsageNotes: The CEDS ISO 639-2 Language Code option set comes from the <a href="http://www.loc.gov/standards/iso639-2/langhome.html">ISO 639-2 standard</a>, the character encoding in ISO 8859-1 download.  Discontinued codes from the ISO standard are not included in the CEDS list.

ElementName: Assessment Need Keyword Translation Language Type
Definition: Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the default language for the keyword translation.
UsageNotes: The CEDS ISO 639-2 Language Code option set comes from the <a href="http://www.loc.gov/standards/iso639-2/langhome.html">ISO 639-2 standard</a>, the character encoding in ISO 8859-1 download.  Discontinued codes from the ISO standard are not included in the CEDS list.

Definition: Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the type of signing preferred by the user.
Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the default presentation mode of the associated Alternative Representations accessibility.

ElementName: Assessment Need Spoken Source Preference Type
Definition: Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the preferred spoken audio form.

ElementName: Assessment Need Read at Start Preference
Definition: Used as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile to define if the spoken play-back should commence from the start of a recording or not.

ElementName: Assessment Need User Spoken Preference Type
Definition: Used as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile to define the type of material that should be rendered using the read aloud alternative content.
Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile whether or not the verbal alternative content presentation should be applied to directive content only.

Defines the multiplier to be applied to the time limit to determine the total testing time allowed when Additional Testing Time is specified as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile.  If the value is `unlimited' then there is no time limit for the test.

ElementName: Assessment Need Line Reader Highlight Color
Definition: The color defined as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile to be used to highlight the point of line reader activity i.e. the line being read.
This is the preferred color for the overlay for screen enhancement defined as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile.
This is the preferred Background color for screen enhancement defined as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile.
Defines the user preferences for white spacing in lines, words and characters as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile.

ElementName: Assessment Personal Needs Profile Assigned Support
Definition: Defines whether or not the individual needs the kind of support defined by the entity.
UsageNotes: This flag may apply to any need within the Assessment Personal Need Profile.

ElementName: Assessment Personal Needs Profile Activate by Default
Definition: Determines if the alternative accessible content is rendered as the default content for the learner.
UsageNotes: This flag may apply to any need within the Assessment Personal Need Profile.

Definition: Specifies as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the type of masks the user is able to create  to cover portions of the question until needed.

ElementName: Assessment Personal Needs Profile Assigned Support
Definition: Defines whether or not the individual needs the kind of support defined by the entity.
UsageNotes: This flag may apply to any need within the Assessment Personal Need Profile.

ElementName: Assessment Personal Needs Profile Activate by Default
Definition: Determines if the alternative accessible content is rendered as the default content for the learner.
UsageNotes: This flag may apply to any need within the Assessment Personal Need Profile.

Definition: The text string that is to be displayed to the user as an expression of encouragement when Masking is specified as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile.  It is left to the system to determine when to display this string.

The URI of the sound file that is to be played to the user as an expression of encouragement when Masking is specified as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile. It is left to the system to determine when to play this audio file.
Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the rating for the collection of Access for All (AfA) needs and preferences.
Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the grade of Braille to use when using a Braille display.

ElementName: Assessment Need Number of Braille Dots Type
Definition: Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the number of dots in a Braille cell.

ElementName: Assessment Need Number of Braille Cells
Definition: Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the number of active Braille cells in a Braille display.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

Definition: Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile what textual properties to mark when using a Braille display.
Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the resistance pressure of Braille display pins.
Format: Numeric - up to 4 digits after decimal place

ElementName: Assessment Need Braille Status Cell Type
Definition: Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the preferred presence or location of a Braille display status cell.
Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the Access for All (AfA) preference to invert the foreground and background Colors.
Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the preferred magnification of the screen as a factor of a screen's original size.
Format: Numeric - up to 4 digits after decimal place

Definition: This is the preferred Foreground color for screen enhancement defined as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile.

ElementName: Assessment Session Actual Start Date Time
Definition: Date and time the assessment actually began.
UsageNotes: When associated to an assessment session this is the actual start date and time.  When associated to an individual taking an assessment, this is the actual date and time when the individual started.

ElementName: Assessment Session Actual End Date Time
Definition: Date and time the assessment actually ended.
UsageNotes: When associated to an assessment session this is the actual end date and time.  When associated to an individual taking an assessment, this is the actual date and time when the individual finished.

Definition: The overall time a learner actually spent during the  assessment session.
The platform with which the assessment was delivered to the student during the assessment session.

ElementName: Assessment Participant Session Delivery Device Details
Definition: The details about the device or platform by with which the assessment was delivered to the learner.
UsageNotes: For example web browser version and screen resolution.

Definition: An unusual event occurred during the administration of the assessment. This could include fire alarm, student became ill, etc.
Describes special events that occur before during or after the assessment session that may impact use of results according to rules related to the Assessment Registration Testing Indicator.
The description of the place where an assessment is administered.
The name of the database that was used to administer the test.
A globally unique identifier for an instance of a person taking an assessment.
UsageNotes: CEDS "GUID" elements are defined as RFC 4122 compliant 32-character hexadecimal strings (36 characters with dashes). For example, 21EC2020-3AEA-1069-A2DD-08002B30309D. <br/><br/>Values MAY be encoded using a hash function such as HMAC-MD5 or HMAC-SHA1, resulting in a string up to 40 characters.

ElementName: Assessment Participant Session Platform User Agent
Definition: A list of product tokens (keywords) with optional comments that identifies the client hardware and software with which the assessment was delivered to the student during the assessment session.
UsageNotes: Implementation Note: The recommended approach is to store the User-Agent string returned as part of an HTTP header.  For example, an assessment session delivery via iPad might have "Mozilla/5.0 (iPad; U; CPU OS 3_2_1 like Mac OS X; en-us) AppleWebKit/531.21.10 (KHTML, like Gecko) Mobile/7B405"

Definition: The metric or scale used for score reporting.
A label representing the performance level appropriate for use on a report.

ElementName: Assessment Performance Level Lower Cut Score
Definition: Lowest possible score for the performance level.

ElementName: Assessment Performance Level Upper Cut Score
Definition: Highest possible score for the performance level.

ElementName: Assessment Personal Needs Profile Assigned Support
Definition: Defines whether or not the individual needs the kind of support defined by the entity.
UsageNotes: This flag may apply to any need within the Assessment Personal Need Profile.

ElementName: Assessment Personal Needs Profile Activate by Default
Definition: Determines if the alternative accessible content is rendered as the default content for the learner.
UsageNotes: This flag may apply to any need within the Assessment Personal Need Profile.

Definition: Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile a preference for the language of the user interface.
UsageNotes: The CEDS ISO 639-2 Language Code option set comes from the <a href="http://www.loc.gov/standards/iso639-2/langhome.html">ISO 639-2 standard</a>, the character encoding in ISO 8859-1 download.  Discontinued codes from the ISO standard are not included in the CEDS list.

Definition: Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the rate of speech of a speech synthesizer.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

Definition: Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the pitch of a speech synthesizer.
Format: Numeric - up to 4 digits after decimal place

Definition: Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the volume of a speech synthesizer.
Format: Numeric - up to 4 digits after decimal place

Definition: Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the characteristics of presentation for a hyperlink when using a screen reader.
A type of need identified for a learner as part of an assessment need profile.

ElementName: Assessment Personal Needs Profile Assigned Support
Definition: Defines whether or not the individual needs the kind of support defined by the entity.
UsageNotes: This flag may apply to any need within the Assessment Personal Need Profile.

Definition: Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile a characteristic of a digital resource that may be specified as being dangerous to a user.
Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the electronic tool associated with a resource.

ElementName: Assessment Need Keyword Translation Language Type
Definition: Defines as part of an Assessment Personal Needs Profile the default language for the keyword translation.
UsageNotes: The CEDS ISO 639-2 Language Code option set comes from the <a href="http://www.loc.gov/standards/iso639-2/langhome.html">ISO 639-2 standard</a>, the character encoding in ISO 8859-1 download.  Discontinued codes from the ISO standard are not included in the CEDS list.

Definition: Date/time assignment is made.
The number of days of instruction the student has taken prior to testing.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

Definition: The date set by the testing program when the test scores are published.  For formative or classroom assessments, this will likely be the date when the scored the individual test.  For summative assessments, this date is likely set for a group of assessments when the processing system releases the scores.
A unique identifier for the test attempt assigned by the delivery system.
UsageNotes: For paper-based tests this is typically a batch/stack/serial number and for online tests it is likely a unique internal identifier. Used to locate the original attempt.<br/><br/>CEDS "Identifier" elements reflect the intent of the XSD:Token format, i.e. a string in which carriage return, line feed, and tab characters have been removed as well as any internal sequences of two or more spaces and any leading or trailing spaces. <br/><br/>An Identifier MAY be a Universally Unique Identifier (UUID) / Globally Unique Identifier (GUID), i.e.128-bit unique identifiers generated according to the algorithms and encoding standards of RFC 4122.

Definition: Indicates if this registration is for a retest (retake). Retest can occur if a student failed a prior attempt and is eligible to retake. Other retest scenarios also can occur.
Indicates rules about use of results based on Special Events before, during or after the test. The option set values are determined by the testing program.
UsageNotes: For example, "do not score", "do not report".

Definition: The unique identifier of the person who assigned the assessment to the learner.
UsageNotes: For example, the unique identifier of a classroom teacher or school principal.<BR/><BR/>CEDS "Identifier" elements reflect the intent of the XSD:Token format, i.e. a string in which carriage return, line feed, and tab characters have been removed as well as any internal sequences of two or more spaces and any leading or trailing spaces. <BR/><BR/>An Identifier MAY be a Universally Unique Identifier (UUID) / Globally Unique Identifier (GUID), i.e.128-bit unique identifiers generated according to the algorithms and encoding standards of RFC 4122.

ElementName: Assessment Registration Completion Status Date Time
Definition: The date and time the completion and scoring status was changed for an instance of a person taking an assessment.
An indication of whether a student was in membership in the state education unit for a full academic year, according to the state's definition of Full Academic Year.
An indication of whether a student was in membership in the LEA education unit for a full academic year, according to the state's definition of Full Academic Year.
An indication of whether a student was in membership in the school education unit for a full academic year, according to the state's definition of Full Academic Year.
An indication of whether a student participated in an assessment.
The primary reason a student is not tested.
The primary reason a participant did not complete an assessment.
UsageNotes: This may apply to any learner, but is used particularly for reporting based on children with disabilities (IDEA).

Definition: The grade or developmental level of a student when assessed.
The grade or developmental level of a student when assessed.
The completion and scoring status for an instance of a person taking an assessment.
The specific method used to report the performance and achievement of the assessment. This is the metric that is being used to derive the scores.
If this score is preliminary, then this attribute value should be set.  Preliminary scores may be provided for early use by the assessment program or user while final scoring is occurring.
The results of a pre-test in academic subjects.

The number of responses that are included with the Student Score Set. Responses are those items that were attempted (partially or fully answered) by the student and not necessarily the number of items in the assessment (which can be determined from the assessment object).
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

Definition: A statement intended for use by education professionals, using professional terminology, to interpret learner needs based on the scored/evaluated portion of an assessment.  This statement may inform Descriptive Feedback given to the learner.
Identifies the source of the Diagnostic Statement based on a scored/evaluated portion of an assessment.

Identifies the source of the descriptive feedback that was given to a learner based on a scored/evaluated portion of an assessment. May indicate if this is teacher, scorer, or system generated feedback. Values for this attribute would be determined by the assessment program.
This provides the next steps for instruction for the student based upon the assessment results and student characteristics.

The most recent date that the result was calculated/updated.  The value should be the same as Assessment Result Date Created if the subtest has only been scored once, but may be different if the score was recalculated with a different result.
UsageNotes: This flag is to handle cases when a subtest result is originally scored using incorrect parameters and then rescored, such as if the grade level attributed to the student was originally encoded incorrectly and later corrected.  An operational system may also capture the history of if rescored more than once.

Definition: The date on which the assessment result was generated.
Use for outcome measures in early learning.
The point in time for which the result is used for an outcome measure.

ElementName: Assessment Result Descriptive Feedback Date Time
Definition: The date and time the descriptive feedback was entered for a scored/evaluated portion of an assessment.
The measure of sampling variability and measurement error for the score, the amount of error to be expected in the score.
UsageNotes: See http://nces.ed.gov/nationsreportcard/NDEHelp/WebHelp/standard_error.htm

Definition: The data type of the assessment result score value.
UsageNotes: An Assessment Result in CEDS may apply to an entire assessment or one aspect of evaluation as defined in the related "subtest" entity.  The Assessment Result entity is repeatable, so there could be multiple Assessment Result Score Values each using a different Assessment Result Data Type, and each of these score values may be associated with one or more Assessment Performance Level(s).

Definition: Indicates the purpose for which this assessment score instance was recorded.

ElementName: Assessment Session Scheduled Start Date Time
Definition: Date and time the assessment is scheduled to begin.

ElementName: Assessment Session Scheduled End Date Time
Definition: Date and time the assessment is scheduled to end.
UsageNotes: All CEDS Exit and End Dates represent the last day of the date range specified, such as the last day that a person was enrolled, participated, or received services.

Definition: The type of session that is scheduled.
The description of the place where an assessment is administered.
The type of role served related to the administration of an assessment session.
The type of identifier that is provided for a Subtest.
The shortened name identifying the assessment for use in reference and/or reports.
The maximum value for the measurement.
The minimum value possible for the measurement.
The optimal value for this measurement.
UsageNotes: The Optimal Value may be the same as the Maximum Value, the Minimum Value, or something in between.

Definition: In a hierarchy of subtests, this element represents the level of the sub test in the hierarchy.  The top tier and default is zero.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

Definition: In a hierarchy of subtests, this indicates that this tier is only used as a level in the hierarchy and does not represent a scoring model.
A description of the rules to produce a student test/subtest score from for a grouping of student item scores.
An indication as to whether an assessment conforms to a standard.

ElementName: Assessment Form Subtest Item Weight Correct
Definition: A weighting factor for how the item score is used to compute a sub-test score when the item is correct or partially correct. Item weight of 1 indicates the full item score is used. A weight of .5 would indicate the item only contributes one half of the item score to the subtest. A weight of 0 indicates the item does not affect the sub test score.

ElementName: Assessment Form Subtest Item Weight Incorrect
Definition: A weighting factor for how the item score is used to compute a sub-test score when the item is attempted and incorrect. Item weight should be a negative value if the item subtracts from the score if missed.

ElementName: Assessment Form Subtest Item Weight Not Attempted
Definition: A weighting factor for how the item score is used to compute a sub-test score when the item has not been attempted by the student. Item weight should be a negative value if the item subtracts from the score if not attempted.
The name of a provider that can authenticate the identity of an person.
The Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) of the  Authentication Identity Provider.
The login identifier for the person for the specified Authentication Identity Provider.
UsageNotes: CEDS "Identifier" elements reflect the intent of the XSD:Token format, i.e. a string in which carriage return, line feed, and tab characters have been removed as well as any internal sequences of two or more spaces and any leading or trailing spaces. <br/><br/>An Identifier MAY be a Universally Unique Identifier (UUID) / Globally Unique Identifier (GUID), i.e.128-bit unique identifiers generated according to the algorithms and encoding standards of RFC 4122.

Definition: The date after which the  an associated person is no longer allowed to use the specified Authentication Identity Provider to authenticate identity.
UsageNotes: All CEDS Exit and End Dates represent the last day of the date range specified, such as the last day that a person was enrolled, participated, or received services.

Definition: The user role for which the person is allowed.
Indicates authorizer agreement to a document or plan, such as plan for delivery of student services, program, or improvement plan.
The date the authorization occurred.
Authorizer's explanation regarding the authorization decision.
Type of person who authorized the decision or document.
A description of the space, as determined by its physical layout and built-in systems and equipment.
The primary use of a space, as determined by its physical layout and built-in systems and equipment, regardless of its original design.
The space designed primarily for conducting administrative and business functions.
The space designed to support the teaching and learning of 2 dimensional or 3 dimensional visual arts.
An area designed primarily for theater productions, assemblies, and other large gatherings.
A classroom designed for instruction of a particular age group, but not a specific subject.

The classroom, laboratory, or shop specially located, designed, furnished, and equipped to support instruction of technical and technology related curriculum, usually tied to particular industry, for example, bio-tech, construction, or agriculture.
A space designed to enable people to move within the building.
The space located, designed, furnished and equipped to support meal programs.
The type of kitchen housed in the facility as defined by whether it prepares food to be served onsite and/or at additional locations.

ElementName: Building Indoor Athletic or Physical Education Space Type
Definition: The indoor space designed, located, furnished, and equipped for instruction and support of a physical education curriculum and athletic program.

ElementName: Building Library or Media Center Specialty Space Type
Definition: The primary and auxiliary space designed to provide and support student and staff access to books, periodicals, software, videos, and the Internet.

ElementName: Building Operations or Maintenance Space Type
Definition: The area designed primarily for conducting activities concerned with maintaining the grounds, buildings, and equipment.

ElementName: Building Outdoor Athletic or Physical Education Space Type
Definition: The outdoor space designed, located, furnished, and equipped for instruction and support of a physical education curriculum and athletic program.

ElementName: Building Outdoor or Non-athletic Space Type
Definition: The outdoor space located, designed, furnished, and equipped primarily for recreation, play and outdoor environmental education.

ElementName: Building Performing Arts Specialty Space Type
Definition: The space designed, located, furnished, and equipped for instruction and support of music and drama curricula and productions.
The space designed, located, furnished, and equipped for instruction and experimentation in science.
The primary design or purpose of a space, as determined by its physical layout and built-in systems and equipment, regardless of its current use.

ElementName: Building Special Education Specialty Space Type
Definition: The space designed, located, furnished, and equipped to support instruction of children with special physical, emotional, and/or educational needs.
The space designed to provide student support services such as administrative, technical (e.g., guidance and health), and logistical support to facilitate and enhance instruction.
An indication that the instruction space in a school is used in the calculation of student capacity.
A designation as to whether the space is included in the calculation of school building capacity under state or local guidelines.

The area in square feet measured between the principal wall that faces at or near floor level, including alcove spaces, and the outer limits of space designed to serve the activity. Structural space is excluded.
Format: Numeric - up to 2 digits after decimal place

Definition: An indication that the space in a school, including circulation, administration offices, support spaces, and common areas, is not part of the calculation for capacity.
The space designed primarily for community or shared use.
A designation as to whether the space is considered an instructional space under state or local guidelines.
The primary means by which air is circulated, freshened, and exhausted.

ElementName: Building Communications Management Component System Type
Definition: The type of system, interface, and management components for carrying voice, video, and data throughout a building.
The type of mechanical systems and building designs used for cooling.
The components and system required to distribute electricity throughout the building or site.
The type of system that protects the facility against fire.
The method by which the heat is distributed and delivered throughout the room(s) or building.
The building service system that provides for heating, ventilation and air-conditioning.
Mechanical means for moving people and equipment within buildings.
The major manufactured systems required to operate a building.
The component of an on-site system for supplying, eliminating, and treating water.
The type of system that protects the facility from intrusion.
The type of system that is installed in the building or site.
The means through which voice, video, audio, and data information are conveyed.
The type of system used to convey persons or freight between floors.
The year in which the system, component, equipment, or fixture was originally installed.
The total cost of acquiring, owning, operating, and disposing of a building, facility, or piece of equipment over its useful life.
Format: Numeric - up to 2 digits after decimal place

Definition: The anticipated time (in years) from the time of installation or service that a properly maintained system, component, equipment, or fixture is expected to operate effectively and efficiently.
Equipment that is installed for use in support of instructional program such as kilns for art, planetarium equipment for astronomy, fitness equipment for physical education.
Moveable assets that are provided so the building or interior assets can be utilized by occupants for their intended purposes.
The rating of the system or component functions under the demands of its regular operation.

ElementName: Component or Fixture Scheduled Serviced Date
Definition: The month, day, and year a major component, system, equipment, or fixture is scheduled to be serviced for preventive or routine maintenance.
The month, day, and year a system, component, equipment, or fixture was serviced for repair or routine maintenance.
A unique number or alphanumeric code assigned to a room by a school, school system, state, or other agency or entity.
UsageNotes: CEDS "Identifier" elements reflect the intent of the XSD:Token format, i.e. a string in which carriage return, line feed, and tab characters have been removed as well as any internal sequences of two or more spaces and any leading or trailing spaces. <br/><br/>An Identifier MAY be a Universally Unique Identifier (UUID) / Globally Unique Identifier (GUID), i.e.128-bit unique identifiers generated according to the algorithms and encoding standards of RFC 4122.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Prerequisite Identifier, Competency Item Prerequisite Identifier
Definition: The unique identifier of an immediate prerequisite Competency Definition, a competency needed prior to learning this one. (Some items may have no prerequisites while others may have one or more prerequisites. This should only be used to represent the immediate predecessors in a competency-based pathway, i.e. not prerequisites of prerequisites.)
UsageNotes: The recommended approach is to use the entity Learning Standard Item Association instead of this data element. Learning Standard Item Association also supports associating other entities, such as Learning Resources, to learning standard items.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Association Identifier URI
Definition: A URI that establishes uniqueness of an association between a competency definition and another competency item or other objects such as learning resources.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Association Connection Citation
Definition: Any citation appropriate to evidence the connection between nodes

AltName: Learning Standard Item Association Origin Node Name
Definition: Name of the origin node when the Competency Association is used as a connector in a learning map.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Association Origin Node URI
Definition: URI of the origin node when the Competency Association is used as a connector in a learning map.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Association Destination Node Name
Definition: Name of the destination node when the Competency Association is used as a connector in a learning map.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Association Destination Node URI
Definition: URI of the destination node when the Competency Association is used as a connector in a learning map.
Indicates the relative significance this connection has for the destination node in a learning map.
Format: Numeric - up to 3 digits after decimal place
UsageNotes: This element is used to support learning maps and may be used in two ways 1) use a 1.000 to flag incoming nodes as important prerequisites/predecessors and 0.000 to indicate those with less significance, or 2) to indicate a levels of significance for the connection as a decimal between 0.000 and 1.000.

Definition: Defines the nature of the association between a Competency Definition and an associated data object such as a Learning Resource, an Assessment Item, or even another Competency Definition.
UsageNotes: The Learning Standard Item Association entity defines metadata relationships between a Learning Standard Item and other objects or relationships between Learning Standard Items not otherwise defined in the normal taxonomy of the framework such as for competency-based pathways, relationships between different versions of the same learning standard, and relationships to resources. <br /><BR/><BR/>For example, "Prerequisite" may indicate that the Associated Learning Standard Item is a Prerequisite of this Learning Standards Item.  Another association may specify that a Learning Resource "Teaches" the specified Learning Standard Item, or is aligned to the "Reading Level" specified as part of the Learning Standard Item.

Definition: The alignment relationship between the resource and a competency definition object.
UsageNotes: A community of SEAs have agreed to use a limited set of Learning Resource Competency Alignment Type options when tagging learning resources in shared resource repositories. Those options are assesses, teaches, and requires.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Education Level, Competency Item Education Level
Definition: The education level, grade level or primary instructional level at which a Competency Definition is intended.
UsageNotes: More than one Learning Standard Grade Level may be associated with one Learning Standard Item.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Type, Competency Item Type
Definition: The class of statement in the structure of statements in the Competency Framework according to a controlled vocabulary, specified as a textual label.
UsageNotes: This property points to a class, not to instances of that class. For example, where two competencies in a competency framework have been identified respectively  as \"Strand: Renaissance\" and \"Strand: Social history\", the competencyCategory for both these competencies is \"Strand\"."

AltName: Learning Standard Item Statement, Competency Item Statement
Definition: The text of the statement. The textual content that either describes a specific competency or describes a less granular group of competencies within the taxonomy of the competency framework.
UsageNotes: Note: This element is designed to support statements from various learning standards frameworks. The Head Start Child Outcomes Framework includes statements for Domains, Elements, and Indicators. Examples from the K-12 Common Core State Standards are the domain: "Geometry", the cluster: "Understand and apply the Pythagorean Theorem," and standard:  "Apply the Pythagorean Theorem to determine unknown side lengths in right triangles in real-world and mathematical problems in two and three dimensions."

AltName: Learning Standard Item Text Complexity System, Competency Item Text Complexity System
Definition: The scaling system used to specify the text complexity of a competency item.

ElementName: Competency Definition Text Complexity Minimum Value
AltName: Learning Standard Item Text Complexity Minimum Value, Competency Item Text Complexity Minimum Value
Definition: The minimum value in the range of text complexity applicable to a language competency definition using the scaling system defined by Text Complexity System, e.g. Lexile(tm).

ElementName: Competency Definition Text Complexity Maximum Value
AltName: Learning Standard Item Text Complexity Maximum Value, Competency Item Text Complexity Maximum Value
Definition: The maximum value in the range of text complexity applicable to a language competency definition using the scaling system defined by Text Complexity System, e.g. Lexile(tm).

AltName: Learning Standard Item Concept Term, Competency Item Concept Term
Definition: The topicality of the competency definition, e.g. "Pythagorean Theorem," "Trigonometric functions," "Forces and energy," "Scientific method," "Oral history," etc.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Concept Keyword, Competency Item Concept Keyword
Definition: The significant topicality of the competency definition using free-text keywords and phrases.

AltName: Learning Standard Item License, Competency Item License
Definition: The full text or URL reference to a legal document giving official permission to do something with the competency definition statement.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Notes, Competency Item Notes
Definition: Information about the derivation of a Competency Definition Statement.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Parent Identifier, Competency Item Parent Identifier
Definition: The globally unique identifier (GUID) issued by the publisher of the competency framework that uniquely identifies the parent item in the hierarchy of competency definitions using a RFC 4122 compliant 32-character hexadecimal string, such as 21EC2020-3AEA-1069-A2DD-08002B30309D.
UsageNotes: CEDS "Identifier" elements reflect the intent of the XSD:Token format, i.e. a string in which carriage return, line feed, and tab characters have been removed as well as any internal sequences of two or more spaces and any leading or trailing spaces. <br/><br/>An Identifier MAY be a Universally Unique Identifier (UUID) / Globally Unique Identifier (GUID), i.e.128-bit unique identifiers generated according to the algorithms and encoding standards of RFC 4122.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Parent Code, Competency Item Parent Code
Definition: A human-referenceable code designated by the publisher to identify the parent item in the hierarchy of competency definitions.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Parent URL, Competency Item Parent URL
Definition: A network-resolvable Uniform Resource Locator (URL) pointing to the authoritative reference for the hierarchal parent of the competency definition.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Current Version Indicator, Competency Item Current Version Indicator
Definition: Indicates that this is the most current version of the Competency Definition.
UsageNotes: This element supports version histories at the statement level. If corrections have been made to individual items/statements that are not part of a new Competency Framework, the elements 'Competency Definition Previous Version Identifier' and 'Competency Definition Current Version Indicator' provide a reference to historical versions of the current statement. In such uses the 'Competency Definition Code' could be the same for multiple versions of a statement and 'Competency Definition URL' could resolve to the most current version of the statement.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Previous Version Identifier, Competency Item Previous Version Identifier
Definition: The unique identifier of the previous version of the Competency Definition if the statement was modified.
UsageNotes: This element supports version histories at the statement level. If corrections have been made to individual items/statements that are not part of a new Competency Framework, the elements 'Competency Definition Previous Version Identifier' and 'Competency Definition Current Version Indicator' provide a reference to historical versions of the current statement. In such uses the 'Competency Definition Code' could be the same for multiple versions of a statement and 'Competency Definition URL' could resolve to the most current version of the statement.<br/><br/><BR/>CEDS "Identifier" elements reflect the intent of the XSD:Token format, i.e. a string in which carriage return, line feed, and tab characters have been removed as well as any internal sequences of two or more spaces and any leading or trailing spaces.<br/><br/><BR/>An Identifier MAY be a Universally Unique Identifier (UUID) / Globally Unique Identifier (GUID), i.e.128-bit unique identifiers generated according to the algorithms and encoding standards of RFC 4122.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Valid Start Date, Competency Item Valid Start Date
Definition: The year, month and day the competency definition was adopted by the jurisdiction in which it was intended to apply.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Valid End Date, Competency Item Valid End Date
Definition: The year, month and day the competency definition was deprecated/replaced by the jurisdiction in which it was intended to apply.
UsageNotes: When not specified, the entity is assumed to contain the most current version of the specified competency definition. All CEDS Exit and End Dates represent the last day of the date range specified, in this case the last day the competency definition was valid.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Sequence, Competency Item Sequence
Definition: A set of one or more alphanumeric characters and/or symbols denoting the positioning of the statement being described in a sequential listing of statements.
UsageNotes: Based on ASN's ListID. (add reference URL)

Definition: The class of statement in the structure of statements in the Competency Framework according to a controlled vocabulary, specified as a URI referencing a controlled vocabulary.
UsageNotes: This property points to a class, not to instances of that class. For example, where two competencies in a competency framework have been identified respectively  as \"Strand: Renaissance\" and \"Strand: Social history\", the competency category for both these competencies is \"Strand\"."

ElementName: Competency Definition Typical Age Range Maximum
Definition: The typical maximum age at which a person learns the defined competency.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0
UsageNotes: Use this element with "Competency Definition Typical Age Range Minimum" instead of "Competency Item Typical Age Range"

ElementName: Competency Definition Typical Age Range Minimum
Definition: The typical minimum age at which a person learns the defined competency.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0
UsageNotes: Use this element with "Competency Definition Typical Age Range Maximum" instead of "Competency Item Typical Age Range"

AltName: Learning Standard Item Blooms Taxonomy Domain, Competency Item Blooms Taxonomy Domain
Definition: Classification of the Competency Definition using Bloom's Taxonomy Domains.�

AltName: Learning Standard Item Multiple Intelligence, Competency Item Multiple Intelligence
Definition: Classification of the Competency Definition using intelligences defined for Howard Earl Gardner's Theory of Multiple Intelligences.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Node Accessibility Profile, Competency Item Node Accessibility Profile
Definition: When the Competency Definition is used as a node in a learning map, this element supports alternative pathways based on a learner's accessibility profile. The type selected indicates which accessibility profile the node is designed to address.

AltName: Learning Standard Item Testability Type, Competency Item Testability Type
Definition: Indicates if the competency described in the Competency Definition Statement can be tested using one or more assessment items.
An unambiguous reference to the competency framework using a network-resolvable URI.
The topic or academic subject of the competency framework.
The person or organization chiefly responsible for the intellectual content of the competency framework.
UsageNotes: Implementations may choose to model this element as a repeatable field to support the case of multiple authors.  Others may just use a comma delimited string for multiple authors.

Definition: A legal, quasi-legal, organizational or institutional domain of the entity mandating the use of the statement--e.g., California.
The entity responsible for making the competency framework available.
The publication status of the competency framework.
The information about rights held in and over the resource.
The person or organization owning or managing rights over the competency framework.
The date on which this content was first published.
UsageNotes: This may or may not be different from the Learning Standard Document Valid Start Date.

Definition: A URL that resolves to the original or authoritative competency framework document.
UsageNotes: This is the URL of a human-readable artifact. Often this document is published in html and/or pdf and is used by the standard setting entity as part of its approval process.

Definition: The criteria for the set of competencies that represent completion or partial completion of a unit, course, program, degree, certification, or other achievement/award. Specifies whether completion requires achievement of all items in the set or some number of items.
UsageNotes: The criteria may be `all' competencies in the set or `at-least' # of competencies. Sets may be nested, e.g. all in subset A and 3 of 5 from subset B.

Definition: The minimum number of competencies in the set that must be achieved for completion or partial completion of a unit, course, program, degree, certification, or other achievement/award.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0
UsageNotes: Used to define the completion criteria when Competency Set Completion Criteria is "At Least".  Not used when Competency Set Completion Criteria is "All".

Definition: A description of the core knowledge areas addressed by Early Learning professional development.
The alphabetic abbreviation of the academic department or discipline offering the course. It is one part of the total course identifier number.
ChangeNotes: Added elements to DES contexts to support post-secondary needs

ElementName: School Courses for the Exchange of Data Sequence of Course
Definition: Where a specific course lies when it is part of a consecutive sequence of courses. This element should be interpreted as "part 'n' of 'm' parts.
UsageNotes: For example: if a school offers 4 years of Theater, Theater 3 within this school would be indicated in the sequence elements as 3 4, denoting the 3rd part of a 4-part sequence of courses.

Definition: The total number of instruction minutes in a given session, as determined by time in class, time on task (e.g., engaged in a class), or as estimated by a qualified course designer.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

Definition: The amount of credit available to the student who successfully meets the objectives of the course or learning opportunity based on the units defined by Credit Unit Type.
Format: Numeric - up to 2 digits after decimal place
UsageNotes: For K-12 a course meeting every day for one period of the school day over the span of a school year typically offers one Carnegie unit. In this case a Carnegie unit is  a measure of "seat time" rather than a measure of attainment of the course objectives.

Definition: A description of the certification or recognition associated with this course (ex. Networking, CAD, etc.)
The maximum number of times the course may be taken or completed for credit.
An indication of the general nature and difficulty of instruction provided throughout a course.
ChangeNotes: Added options to align with the Migrant Student Information (MSIX) data collections.

Definition: The type of credit (unit, semester, or quarter) associated with the credit hours earned for the course.
ChangeNotes: Added elements to DES contexts to support post-secondary needs

Definition: The language of instruction, other than English, used in the program or course.
UsageNotes: The CEDS ISO 639-2 Language Code option set comes from the <a href="http://www.loc.gov/standards/iso639-2/langhome.html">ISO 639-2 standard</a>, the character encoding in ISO 8859-1 download.  Discontinued codes from the ISO standard are not included in the CEDS list.

Definition: The education level, grade level or primary instructional level at which a course is intended.
UsageNotes: This element is repeatable for most use cases.  Examples: (1.) SCED identifiers may specify a grade span of two or more grades.  (2) A postsecondary course designed to qualify a student for an associates degree and professional certification could be repeated with both of those options.

Definition: Measured in Carnegie units, the amount of credit available to a student who successfully meets the objectives of the course. A course meeting every day for one period of the school day over the span of a school year offers one Carnegie unit. A Carnegie unit is thus a measure of "seat time" rather than a measure of attainment of the course objectives.
Format: Numeric - up to 2 digits after decimal place

ElementName: Course Section Time Required for Completion
Definition: The actual or estimated number of clock minutes required for course completion. This number is especially important for career and technical education course and may represent (in minutes) the clock hour requirement of the course, the number of minutes (or clock hours) of class time per week, times the number of equivalent weeks the class typically meets.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

Definition: Indicates a school, institution, program, or course section focuses primarily on instruction in which students and teachers are separated by time and/or location and interact through the use of computers and/or telecommunications technologies.
The year, month and day an instance of a course officially began.
The maximum number of students the Course Section can maintain.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

AltName: Related Learning Standard Items, Related Competency Items
Definition: An indication of the competency definition(s) addressed in the Course Section.
The primary setting or medium of delivery for the course.

ElementName: Course Section Single Sex Class Status
Definition: Section in a co-educational school where only male or only female students are permitted to take the course.
The type of credits or units of value available for the completion of a course in addition to Carnegie Units.
Course areas for advanced placement or credit.  For a list of codes see http://apcentral.collegeboard.com/apc/public/courses/teachers_corner/index.html .
