Type of natural hazard that can affect the health, safety and operation of school facilities and their occupants.
The reasons for permitting and participating in joint-use.
The types of users sharing school district controlled, owned, or utilized facilities.
The type of designation of non school district users by the amount of time they have access to public school for joint use.
The amount of money the school must pay to rent the facility that it is in.
Format: Numeric - up to 2 digits after decimal place

Definition: The category of payment that a school must pay to rent the facility that it is in.

The type of agreement that allows the use and possession of a school, building, or other facility from a third party in return for a regularly scheduled installment payment over an agreed-upon period.

ElementName: Building Charter School Realty Access Type
Definition: The type of real estate vehicle through which a public charter school has access and control of its building space.
The standard for cleanliness, and benchmarks for how much space can be assigned to one properly supplied custodian to meet these standards.
The type of management organization for planning, design, and construction of major capital projects.
The type of agency that has ultimate responsibility for the compliance determination.
The type of management arrangements whereby a district oversees and manages its facilities operations.
A description of the management and accountability plan.
The type of management and accountability plan.
The type of abnormal and urgent circumstances that disrupt the normal operation of the building, threaten the health and safety of the occupants, or require an emergency response.

ElementName: Facility State or Local Mandate Name
Definition: The specific law, rule, regulation, or standard of a state or local government that pertains to public school facilities.
The authority that mandates through law, regulation, or standard that pertains to a specific mandate.
The particular federal law, regulation, or standard that pertains to a school facility.
The area of interest controlled by a federal law, regulation, or standard that pertains to a school facility.

ElementName: Facility State or Local Mandate Interest Type
Definition: The area of interest controlled by a law, rule, regulation, or standard of state and local governments that pertains to public school facilities.
The amount the borrower pays the lender to compensate the lender for the use of money to purchase a building or facility.
Format: Numeric - up to 2 digits after decimal place

Definition: The total assessed value of property that constitutes the basis for public borrowing.
Format: Numeric - up to 2 digits after decimal place

Definition: The type of interest paid on a mortgage to the lender to compensate the lender for the use of money to purchase a building or facility.
The status of a mortgage as it relates to priority of payment.
The type of fee that one must pay when getting a mortgage.
The physical layout and character of a school facility, as determined by age groups served and educational programs provided.
The lot and square number, or equivalent unique municipal number identification, of a parcel of land.

The total number of acres in a continuous piece of land, to the nearest tenth, including undeveloped areas as well as areas occupied by buildings, walks, drives, parking facilities, and other improvements.
Format: Numeric - up to 1 digit after decimal place

Definition: A characterization of a site that would define restrictions or opportunities.
The designated constructed outdoor area on a public school site.

ElementName: Building Hours of Public Use Per Week
Definition: The number of hours that all or part of a building is used for purposes other than general education by the community or other organizations.

ElementName: Building Net Area of Instructional Space
Definition: The area of space directly used for instruction excluding circulation, administration, student services, and building support.
Format: Numeric - up to 2 digits after decimal place

Definition: The number of teaching stations, as defined by how many spaces have, or could have, a teacher assigned to them for classroom instruction.
A description of the policy that enables the community or other organizations to use all or part of a building for purposes other than general education.
The maximum number of age appropriate students who can be enrolled in a facility such that the district's programmatic, operational, and student/teacher work load requirements are met.

A number given to a financial account within a local source accounting system. The number may be a concatenation of a standard  prefix for the type of account with digits added that have specific meaning within the local system.
A label for a grouping of financial accounts, based on type and purpose.

A fund is a separate fiscal and accounting entity with a self-balancing set of accounts recording cash and other financial resources, together with all related liabilities and residual equities or balances or changes therein.
UsageNotes: Based on codes specified in the NCES Handbook <a href="http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2015/fin_acct/chapter6_1.asp">"Financial Accounting for Local and State School Systems: 2014 Edition"</a>.

Definition: A program is a plan of activities and procedures designed to accomplish a predetermined objective or set of objectives.  The program classification provides the school district with a framework to classify instructional and other expenditures by program to determine cost.
UsageNotes: Based on codes specified in the NCES Handbook <a href="http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2015/fin_acct/chapter6_2.asp">"Financial Accounting for Local and State School Systems: 2014 Edition"</a>.

ElementName: Financial Account K12 Balance Sheet Code
Definition: Balance sheet accounts and statement of net position accounts are used to track financial transactions for each fund. Such financial statements only report assets, deferred outflows of resources, liabilities, deferred inflows of resources, and equity accounts and are considered "snapshots" of how these accounts stand as of a certain point in time.
UsageNotes: Based on codes specified in the NCES Handbook <a href="http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2015/fin_acct/chapter6_3.asp">"Financial Accounting for Local and State School Systems: 2014 Edition"</a>.

Definition: The function describes the activity for which a service or material object is acquired. The functions of a school district are classified into five broad areas: instruction, support services, operation of noninstructional services, facilities acquisition and construction, and debt service. Functions are further classified into sub functions.
UsageNotes: Based on codes specified in the NCES Handbook <a href="http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2015/fin_acct/chapter6_5.asp">"Financial Accounting for Local and State School Systems: 2014 Edition"</a>.

Definition: This classification is used to describe the service or commodity obtained as the result of a specific expenditure.  Nine major object categories have codes ending in 00 and are further subdivided.
UsageNotes: Based on codes specified in the NCES Handbook <a href="http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2015/fin_acct/chapter6_6.asp">"Financial Accounting for Local and State School Systems: 2014 Edition"</a>.

Definition: A number given to a financial account within a local source accounting system. The number may be a concatenation of a standard  prefix for the type of account with digits added that have specific meaning within the local system.

ElementName: Financial Expenditure K12 Project Reporting Code
Definition: The project/reporting code permits school districts to accumulate expenditures to meet a variety of specialized reporting requirements at the local, state, and federal levels. It is a three-digit code with the format 00X.   The first two digits identify the particular funding source, authority, or expenditure purpose for which a special record or report is required. The third digit is available to identify particular projects and the fiscal year of the appropriation within that funding source. Each classification is presented by a code range followed by a description.
UsageNotes: Based on the following code conventions specified in the NCES Handbook <a href="http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2015/fin_acct/chapter6_7.asp">"Financial Accounting for Local and State School Systems: 2014 Edition"</a>:<BR/><BR/>010 to 190 Local Projects. Expenditures that require specialized reporting and are funded from local sources. <BR/><BR/>200 to 390 State Projects. Expenditures that require specialized reporting for categorically funded state programs.<BR/><BR/>400 to 990 Federal Projects. Expenditures that require specialized reporting to the federal government directly or through the state.<BR/><BR/>1000 Noncategorical. Expenditures that do not require specialized reporting.

ElementName: Financial Expenditure K12 Level of Instruction Code
Definition: This classification permits expenditures to be segregated by instructional level.
UsageNotes: Based on codes specified in the NCES Handbook <a href="http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2015/fin_acct/chapter6_8.asp">"Financial Accounting for Local and State School Systems: 2014 Edition"</a>.

Definition: These codes are for recording revenue and other receivables by source.  Major revenue categories have codes ending in 00 and are further subdivided.
UsageNotes: Based on codes specified in the NCES Handbook <a href="http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2015/fin_acct/chapter6_4.asp">"Financial Accounting for Local and State School Systems: 2014 Edition"</a>.<BR/><BR/>Early Learning: If related to an "in kind" contribution use codes 1920 or 100.

Definition: A number given to a program area within an educational institution's accounting system.
The type of financial application completed by an individual.
UsageNotes: Common Data Set definition.  This element may be repeated multiple times.

Definition: The school year for which the student's financial aid application and award data apply.  Generally, this is the 12-month period from July 1 to June 30.
The classification of financial aid awarded to a person for the academic term/year.
UsageNotes: Linked to financial aid type.<BR/>Note:  For any given individual this cluster of fields may be repeated multiple times.

Definition: An indication of whether the financial aid type being reported is aid that has been awarded, accepted or dispersed.
UsageNotes: Linked to financial aid type, financial aid amount.   <BR/>Note:  For any given individual this field may be repeated multiple times.

Definition: The amount of financial aid awarded to a person for the term/year.
Format: Numeric - up to 2 digits after decimal place
UsageNotes: Linked to financial aid award type.   <BR/>Note:  For any given individual this cluster of fields may be repeated multiple times.

Definition: Frequency of evaluation of progress toward meeting the goal or short-term objective.
One or more statements that describes the criteria used by teachers and students to check for attainment of a goal.
Type of evidence appropriate for assessing achievement of a goal or short-term objective.
The percent of correct results that will be considered to represent successful achievement of a goal.
Format: Numeric - between 0 and 1, up to 2 digits

Definition: The number of attempts representing a completed trial for assessing achievement of a goal.
A metric used for evaluating achievement of a goal.
The number of correct results that will be considered to represent successful achievement of a goal.
Current performance explanation related to the annual goal or short-term objectives.
Description of status toward achievement of the annual goal or short-term objectives.
Status toward achievement of the annual goal or short-term objectives.
Category of evaluation used for IDEA eligibility.
Type of Individualized Education Plan document authorized.
Portion the authorizer does not want executed.
Authorizer's explanation for rejected portions.
How the child's disability affects the child's academic achievement.
How the child's disability affects the child's functional performance.

ElementName: IEP Present Level General Education Description
Definition: How the child's disability affects the child's involvement and progress in the general education curriculum.

ElementName: IEP Present Level Parent Concern Description
Definition: Parent's explanation of their interest in or concerns about the student's participation in special education.
For preschool children, as appropriate, how the disability affects the child's participation in appropriate activities.

ElementName: IEP Present Level Student Concern Description
Definition: Student's explanation of his or her interest in or concerns about participation in special education.

ElementName: IEP Present Level Student Strengths Description
Definition: Explanation of perceived strengths and abilities of the student.

A locally assigned unique identifier (within the school or school district) to identify each specific incident or occurrence. The same identifier should be used to document the entire incident even if it included multiple offenses and multiple offenders.
UsageNotes: CEDS "Identifier" elements reflect the intent of the XSD:Token format, i.e. a string in which carriage return, line feed, and tab characters have been removed as well as any internal sequences of two or more spaces and any leading or trailing spaces. <br/><br/>An Identifier MAY be a Universally Unique Identifier (UUID) / Globally Unique Identifier (GUID), i.e.128-bit unique identifiers generated according to the algorithms and encoding standards of RFC 4122.

Definition: The year, month and day on which the incident occurred.
An indication of the time of day the incident took place.
A code for the description of the time of day that an incident took place.
The description for an incident.
Categories of behavior coded for use in describing an incident.
Supplemental information about an incident when the primary offense is more serious in nature than alcohol or drug, etc. offenses.
An indication of the occurrence of physical injury to participants involved in the incident and, if so, the level of injury sustained.
UsageNotes: Incident Injury Type can be linked to any person involved in the incident.

Definition: Identifies the type of weapon used during an incident.
UsageNotes: See Forum Guide to Crime, Violence, and Discipline Incident Data http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2011/2011806.pdf Forum Guide.

Definition: The value of any quantifiable monetary loss directly resulting from the incident. Examples include the value of repairs necessitated by vandalism of a school facility, the value of personnel resources used for repairs or consumed by the incident, the value of stolen items, and the value of time consumed by an incident (e.g., instructional time involved in evacuating a school during a false fire alarm).  Cost may be reported by specific monetary amount or range.
Identifies the reporter of the incident using  a pre-existing unique student identifier or unique staff identifier, when the reporter is a student or staff member.
UsageNotes: CEDS "Identifier" elements reflect the intent of the XSD:Token format, i.e. a string in which carriage return, line feed, and tab characters have been removed as well as any internal sequences of two or more spaces and any leading or trailing spaces. <br/><br/>An Identifier MAY be a Universally Unique Identifier (UUID) / Globally Unique Identifier (GUID), i.e.128-bit unique identifiers generated according to the algorithms and encoding standards of RFC 4122.

Definition: Information on the type of person who reported the incident. When known and/or if useful, use a more specific option code (e.g., "Counselor" rather than "Professional Staff").
Identifies where the incident occurred and whether or not it occurred on campus.
The type of firearm.
A description of the rule, regulation, or standard that was violated when an incident occurred (e.g., the identification of a relevant law, conduct standard, or acceptable use policy).
An indication whether a student's behavior (offense) was a manifestation of, or related to, a disability condition.
UsageNotes: Under IDEA 300.530(e), a manifestation determination must occur within 10 days of any decision to change the child's placement because of a violation of a code of student conduct.

ElementName: Incident Reported to Law Enforcement Indicator
Definition: An indication that the school resource officer or any other law enforcement official was notified about the incident, regardless of whether official action is taken.
An indication of whether the offense was primary or secondary in nature when a single incident included more than one type of offense.
An indication of the occurrence of physical injury to the perpetrator(s) (participants) involved in the incident and, if so, the level of injury sustained.
The role or type of participation of a person in a discipline incident.

Information on the type of individual who committed an incident. A "perpetrator" is an individual involved in an incident as an offender (the person who committed the infraction constituting the incident).

ElementName: Individualized Program Service Plan Date Type
Definition: An indication of the significance of a date to an individualized program.
The year, month and day on which the status of an individualized program for a student is significantly altered.

ElementName: Individualized Program NonInclusion Minutes Per Week
Definition: The number of minutes per week that a student with disabilities is served in a regular classroom with his or her non-disabled peers.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

ElementName: Individualized Program Inclusion Minutes Per Week
Definition: The number of minutes per week that a student with disabilities is served in a special education setting separate from his or her non-disabled peers.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

Definition: The post-school transition plan for the student recorded on their Individualized Education Program.
A designation of the type of program developed for a student.
The year, month and day on which the status of the service plan for a child is established or significantly altered.

ElementName: Individualized Program Service Plan Meeting Location
Definition: The place in which a child's service plan meeting is held.

ElementName: Individualized Program Service Plan Meeting Participants
Definition: The position titles of individuals who attend the service plan meeting.

ElementName: Individualized Program Service Plan Signed By
Definition: The position titles of individuals who sign a written service plan.

ElementName: Individualized Program Service Plan Signature Date
Definition: The year, month and day on which the service plan document is signed.

ElementName: Individualized Program Service Plan Reevaluation Date
Definition: Date student will be reevaluated for continued placement in a support program(s).

Type of related or ancillary services offered or provided to a person or a group of persons within the formal educational system or by an outside agency which provides non-instructional services to support the general welfare of students. This includes physical and emotional health, the ability to select an appropriate course of study, admission to appropriate educational programs, and the ability to adjust to and remain in school through the completion of programs. In serving a student with an identified disability, related services include developmental, corrective, or supportive services required to ensure that the person benefits from special education.
UsageNotes: At the organization level, this element indicates the services offered to students. At the person level, this element indicates the services received by students.
ChangeNotes: Added new options to the existing option set

ElementName: Individualized Program Service Plan End Date
Definition: The year, month and day on which the status of the service plan for a child effectively ends.
UsageNotes: All CEDS Exit and End Dates represent the last day of the date range specified, such as the last day that a person was enrolled, participated, or received services.

Definition: Beginning not later than one year before the child reaches the age of majority under State law, the IEP must include a statement that the child has been informed of the child's rights under Part B of the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act, if any, that will transfer to the child on reaching the age of majority under 300.520.
Circumstances in which the accommodation or change to standards or practices will be applied.

ElementName: Individualized Program Service Plan Amendment Reason Description
Definition: Description of the reason changes were made to the individualized program service plan.
A statement of why-
The date the consent to evaluation occurred.
Indication parent agreed to evaluate student.
Explanation of parent's observations of student's characteristics and history used for determining eligibility.
Purpose within the IEP lifecycle for which the eligibility evaluation is conducted.
Legal category for an IEP annual goal or short-term objectives.

ElementName: Individualized Program Service Plan Meeting Date
Definition: The date on which a child's service plan meeting is held.

ElementName: Individualized Program Service Plan Progress Report Description
Definition: A description of the progress report used to notify parents of the student's progress on annual goals and if the progress is sufficient to achieve the goals by the end of the individualized program service plan.

ElementName: Individualized Program Service Plan Progress Report Date
Definition: The date parents are notified of the student's progress on annual goals and if the progress is sufficient to achieve the goals by the end of the individualized program service plan.

ElementName: Individualized Program Service Plan Progress Report Type
Definition: A method by which parents are notified of the student's progress on annual goals and if the progress is sufficient to achieve the goals by the end of the individualized program service plan.

ElementName: Individualized Program Service Plan Progress Report Schedule
Definition: Frequency by which parents are notified of the student's progress on annual goals and if the progress is sufficient to achieve the goals by the end of the individualized program service plan year.
The types of service that adapts the curriculum, materials, or instruction for students identified as needing special education because of a delay or disability.
The method by which the services will be provided.
The frequency that a service is planned to be provided.
The length, in hours, that delivery of the service is planned.
Format: Numeric - up to 2 digits after decimal place

ElementName: Individualized Program Planned Service Start Date
Definition: The date the service is planned to begin.
UsageNotes: As decided on by an IFSP/IEP team, including the parent.

ElementName: IPEDS Finance FASB Financial Position Category
Definition: IPEDS financial position classification used by degree-granting private, not-for-profit institutions and public institutions using FASB Reporting Standards for reporting the assets, liabilities, and net assets in a manner consistent with the Statement of Financial Position in the General Purpose Financial Statements (GPFS).

ElementName: IPEDS Finance FASB Functional Expense Category
Definition: A functional expense classification is a method of grouping expenses according to the purpose for which the costs are incurred. The classifications tell�why�an expense was incurred rather than�what�was purchased.
UsageNotes: (NACUBO FARM, section 700)

ElementName: IPEDS Finance FASB Pell Grant Transactions
Definition: Method of reporting Pell Grants in IPEDS by degree-granting private, not-for-profit institutions and public institutions using FASB Reporting Standards.

IPEDS revenue classification used by degree-granting private, not-for-profit institutions and public institutions using FASB Reporting Standards for reporting revenues and investment return by source in a manner consistent with the definitions from the National Association of College and University Business Officers (NACUBO) Financial Accounting and Reporting Manual for Higher Education (FARM).

ElementName: IPEDS Finance FASB Revenue Restriction Category
Definition: IPEDS revenue restriction classification used by degree-granting private, not-for-profit institutions and public institutions using FASB Reporting Standards for reporting revenues by restriction.

ElementName: IPEDS Finance FASB Scholarships and Fellowships Revenue Category
Definition: IPEDS revenue category used by degree-granting private, not-for-profit institutions and public institutions using FASB Reporting Standards for the reporting of resources received for supporting student grant aid.

ElementName: IPEDS Finance GASB Financial Position Category
Definition: IPEDS financial position classification used by degree-granting public institutions using GASB Reporting Standards for reporting the assets, liabilities, and net position in a manner consistent with the Statement of Net Position in the General Purpose Financial Statements (GPFS).

ElementName: IPEDS Finance GASB Functional Expense Category
Definition: A functional expense classification is a method of grouping expenses according to the purpose for which the costs are incurred. The classifications tell why an expense was incurred rather than what was purchased.
UsageNotes: (NACUBO FARM, section 700)

Definition: IPEDS revenue classification used by degree-granting public institutions using GASB Reporting Standards for reporting revenues and other additions by source including all operating revenues, nonoperating revenues, and other additions for the reporting period. This includes unrestricted and restricted revenues and additions, whether expendable or nonexpendable.

ElementName: IPEDS Finance GASB Scholarships and Fellowships Revenue Category
Definition: IPEDS revenue category used by degree-granting public institutions using GASB Reporting Standards for the reporting of resources received for supporting student scholarships and fellowships.
Identifies the functional expense category where the institution allocates its intercollegiate athletics expenses.

A natural expense classification is a method of grouping expenses according to the type of costs that are incurred. The classifications tell what was purchased rather than why an expense was incurred.
UsageNotes: (NACUBO FARM section 700)

Definition: The type of agency that authorized the establishment or continuation of a charter school.
A program through which the course is funded.
UsageNotes: This may be a program targeted to a specific student population (e.g. SPED, ESOL) and the funding guidelines may specify that all or some of the students in the course are members of the subgroup.

ElementName: Family and Consumer Sciences Course Indicator
Definition: An indication that the course is associated with the Family and Consumer Sciences plan of study.

ElementName: School Courses for the Exchange of Data Grade Span
Definition: The grade span for which the course is appropriate.
UsageNotes: The span is represented by a four-character code with no decimals.  Each grade level from 1 through 12 is represented by a two-digit code, ranging from 01 to 12; kindergarten is represented by the letters KG and prekindergarten by the letters PK.

Definition: A type of formal education program in which a student learns at least in part through online learning, with some element of student control over time, place, path, and/or pace; at least in part in a supervised brick-and-mortar location away from home; and the modalities along each student's learning path within a course or subject are connected to provide an integrated learning experience.
UsageNotes: This may be an attribute of a Course (as designed) or a Class Section (as delivered). It also may be attributed to a school, institution, or program for "whole-school" blended models.

Definition: The primary type of interaction, synchronous or asynchronous, defined for the course.
UsageNotes: This may be an attribute of a Course (as designed) or an instance of a Class Section (as delivered).

Definition: An indication that this course has an end of course examination required by the SEA or LEA.
The type of work-based learning opportunity a student participated in.

ElementName: Local Education Agency Supervisory Union Identification Number
Definition: The three-digit unique identifier assigned to the supervisory union by the state.

An indication that a public school provides free public elementary and/or secondary education to eligible students under a specific charter executed, pursuant to a state charter school law, by an authorized chartering agency/authority and that is designated by such authority to be a public charter school.
UsageNotes: When the element is used for an LEA, it means the LEA is a Charter District meaning any and all schools under the authority of the LEA are charter schools. Don't flag an LEA as a charter district if it has a mix of charter schools and non-charter schools.

Definition: An indication of whether the LEA was able to implement the provisions for public school choice under Title I, Part A, Section 1116 of ESEA as amended.
The total Title V, Part A funds received by LEAs.
Format: Numeric - up to 2 digits after decimal place

Definition: The total Title V, Part A funds expended by LEAs.
Format: Numeric - up to 2 digits after decimal place

ElementName: Innovative Dollars Spent on Strategic Priorities
Definition: The total amount of Title V, Part A funds expended by LEAs for the four strategic priorities.
Format: Numeric - up to 2 digits after decimal place

Definition: The dollar amount spent on transportation for public school choice during the school year under Title I of ESEA as amended, Part A, Section 1116.
Format: Numeric - up to 2 digits after decimal place

Definition: The dollar amount spent on supplemental educational services during the school year under Title I, Part A, Section 1116 of ESEA as amended.
Format: Numeric - up to 2 digits after decimal place

ElementName: Supplemental Education Services Public School Choice Twenty Percent Obligation
AltName: SES Public School Choice Twenty Percent Obligation
Definition: The dollar amount of the 20 percent reservation for supplemental educational services and choice-related transportation.

ElementName: Type of Use of the Rural Low-Income Schools Program
AltName: Type of Use of the RLIS Program
Definition: The type of use of the Rural Low-Income Schools Program (RLIS) (Title VI, Part B, Subpart 2) Grant Funds.
An indication whether the LEA is covered by a desegregation plan either ordered by a court or entered into with the Office for Civil Rights under Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964.
An indication of whether the education unit has adopted written policy prohibiting harassment and bullying on the basis of a civil rights law.

The percentage of funds used to administer assessments required by section 1111(b) or to carry out other activities described in section 6111 and other activities related to ensuring that the State's schools and local educational agencies are held accountable for results.
Format: Numeric - up to 3 digits before and 2 digits after decimal place

Definition: The percentage of funds used to pay the costs of the development of the State assessments and standards required by section 1111(b).
Format: Numeric - up to 3 digits before and 2 digits after decimal place

ElementName: Terminated Title III Programs Due to Failure
Definition: An indication of whether a Title III program or activity was terminated due to failure to meet goals.
The number of interscholastic sports in which only male students participate.  Sports include distinct sports such as football, basketball, soccer but not intramural sports or cheerleading.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

Definition: The number of interscholastic sports in which only female students participate.  Sports include distinct sports such as football, basketball, soccer but not intramural sports or cheerleading.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

Definition: The number of interscholastic teams in which only male students participate.  Teams include each competitive level team in each sport, such as freshman team, junior varsity team, and varsity team but not intramural sports or cheerleading.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

Definition: The number of interscholastic teams in which only female students participate.  Teams include each competitive level team in each sport, such as freshman team, junior varsity team, and varsity team but not intramural sports or cheerleading.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

Definition: The number of male students who participated on an interscholastic team.  A student should be counted once for each team he was on.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

Definition: The number of female students who participated on an interscholastic team.  A student should be counted once for each team she was on.
Format: Integer - greater than or equal to 0

Definition: Barriers to the enrollment and success of homeless children and youths.
An indication of the extent to which the district has effectively and fully integrated technology, as defined by the state.
The groups of students for whom pre-kindergarten programs are available.

ElementName: Prekindergarten Eligible Ages for Non-IDEA Students
Definition: The ages of children not served under IDEA to whom the LEA's pre-kindergarten services are available.
The baseline of the performance indicator of student behavior under the Safe and Drug-Free Schools and Communities Act.

ElementName: Safe and Drug Free Baseline Year
Definition: The academic year the baseline was established.

ElementName: Safe and Drug Free Collection Frequency
Definition: The frequency of data collection for performance indicator under the Safe and Drug-Free Schools and Communities Act.

ElementName: Safe and Drug Free Indicator Name
Definition: The name of the performance indicator for student behaviors under the Safe and Drug-Free Schools and Communities Act.
The instrument or data source for reported performance indicator of student behavior under the Safe and Drug-Free Schools and Communities Act.
Actual performance for the given  indicator of student behavior under the Safe and Drug-Free Schools and Communities Act
The targeted performance for the given  indicator of student behavior under the Safe and Drug-Free Schools and Communities Act.

ElementName: Safe and Drug Free Year Most Recent Collection
Definition: The academic year of the most recent collection of the performance indicator under the Sage and Drug-Free Schools and Communities Act.
The type of Title III professional development utilized.
The type of support services provided to students in Title I programs.
The type of responsibility the district has for the student.

Definition: An indication of the nature of a student's affiliation, as defined by the state, with a public school and used generally, but not exclusively, for the purpose of determining residency, funding, or accountability.
UsageNotes: This element should be used in conjunction with the Public School Residence Status and the Responsible School Type elements to create specificity about the role a school plays or should play in the education of the student.

Definition: An institution/facility/program that serves more than one programming purpose.  For example, the same facility may run both a juvenile correction program and a juvenile detention program.
The portion of a day that a pre-kindergarten program is provided to the students it serves.
The portion of a day that a kindergarten program is provided to the students it serves.
State/local code used to determine a student's eligibility for Gifted/Talented program.
The time of year that a Migrant Education Program operates.
Type of project funded in whole or in part by MEP funds.
The type of instructional services provided to students in ESEA Title I programs.
The type of Title I program offered in the school or district.
The school year in which a charter school was initially approved.
The full name of an agency that accredited a school.

Definition: Indicates that the charter school offers open enrollment.
The effective date of the contract (or charter) that an approved charter school authorizer authorized the charter school to operate in the state under the state's charter school legislation.
The unique number the SEA assigns to the contract (or charter) that authorizes the charter school to operate in the state under the state's charter school legislation.

The date by which the charter school must renew its contract (or charter) with an approved charter school authorizer in order to continue to operate in the state under the state's charter school legislation.

The type of organization that is a separate legal entity that 1) contracts with one or more charter schools to manage, operate, and oversee the charter schools; or 2) holds a charter, or charters, to operate multiple charter schools.
The type of education institution as classified by its primary focus.
An indication of the level of the education institution.
The type of education institution as classified by its funding source.

Definition: The year, month, and day on which the Home Language Survey is known to have been administered to the parent or guardian of this student.
UsageNotes: The actual date of the administration is not what this element is capturing but rather when the result of the home language survey have been received by the school. The survey may have been completed in the school office upon registration of the student or could have been completed at home as part of a set of documents parents or guardians complete when enrolling students. When the completed home language survey has been provided to the school, the date received or the date the information is entered into a student information system as having been completed is sufficient to meet the intent of this element.
ChangeNotes: Added new element to DES

Definition: An indication that the parent or guardian of this student was administered the Home Language Survey - a questionnaire given to parents or guardians that helps schools and local education agencies identify which students are potential English Learners and who will require assessment of their English language proficiency to determine whether they are eligible for language assistance services.
UsageNotes: The term "administration" would indicate that the results of the home language survey for this student have been provided to the school. The intent of this element is not to determine whether or not the school provided a home language survey to the parents/guardians of the student but instead to determine if the school received the results of that home language survey back from the parents/guardians of the student.

Definition: The Uniform Resource Locator where the resource may be accessed, or a proxy for the resource, such as an information page for a commercially available resource.
The descriptive name for the subject of the content for the learning resource.
The code used to identify the organization of subject matter and related learning experiences addressed by the learning resource.
UsageNotes: A promising practice is to use a URL as the Learning Resource Subject Code, that resolves to a web page describing a term in a subject taxonomy.  For example, for "Mathematics", the URL http://id.loc.gov/authorities/classification/BH301.M35.html points to the Library of Congress classification for "Mathematics".  For K12 curriculum "SCED" - School Courses for the Exchange of Data (SCED) may be used, e.g. https://ceds.ed.gov/ScedCourseCodes.aspx#02031 is "Mathematics (grade 1)"

Definition: The system that is used to identify the organization of subject matter and related learning experiences addressed by the learning resource.
UsageNotes: This may be a URL to a web page describing the subject code system or a name or abbreviation for the system if no authoritative web page exists.  When the associated learning resource Subject Code is a URL, that URL usually provides enough context so that the "Subject Code System" need not be specified.  However, this may be the URL to a page describing the classification system and/or the entry point to the web hosted classification system.  E.g. for the Library of Congress Classification System use: http://id.loc.gov/authorities/classification.html

Definition: The predominate type or kind characterizing the learning resource.

Definition: The name of the organization credited with publishing the resource.

Definition: A resource that was used in the creation of this resource. This term can be repeated for multiple sources.

ElementName: Economic Research Service Rural-Urban Continuum Code
Definition: Rural-Urban Continuum Codes form a classification scheme that distinguishes metropolitan (metro) counties by the population size of their metro area, and nonmetropolitan (nonmetro) counties by degree of urbanization and adjacency to a metro area or areas. The metro and nonmetro categories have been subdivided into three metro and six nonmetro groupings, resulting in a nine-part county codification. The codes allow researchers working with county data to break such data into finer residential groups beyond a simple metro-nonmetro dichotomy, particularly for the analysis of trends in nonmetro areas that may be related to degree of rurality and metro proximity.
An indication that the record should not be published.

Children and youth who lack a fixed, regular, and adequate nighttime residence. Homeless children and youth include: 1) children and youth who are sharing the housing of other persons due to loss of housing, economic hardship, or a similar reason; are living in motels, hotels, trailer parks, or camping grounds due to the lack of alternative adequate accommodations; are living in emergency or transitional shelters; are abandoned in hospitals; or are awaiting foster care placement; 2) children and youth who have a primary nighttime residence that is a public or private place not designed for or originally used as a regular sleeping accommodation for human beings; or 3) children and youths who are living in cars, parks, public spaces, abandoned buildings, substandard housing, bus or train stations, or similar settings. 4) migratory children who qualify as homeless because the children are living in circumstances described in the above. (See Section 103 of the McKinney Act for a more detailed description of this data element).

Definition: The last year, month and day when a status applied to an individual.
UsageNotes: This element reflects the end date for a person's status rather than that person's participation in a program. Use Program Participation Exit Date if referring to a person's participation in a program or receipt of services. Status dates and program participation dates don't need to align, they are for different purposes. For example, for a homeless student the Status Begin Date and Status End Date elements are used to record when the student began being homeless to the date when the student ceased being homeless.  The student may begin receiving services under a program for homeless students after becoming homeless and that program may continue to provide services after the student ceases to have the status of "homeless" and therefore have a Program Participation Start Date and Program Participation Exit Date that are different from the status dates.  Students under the McKinney-Vento may continue to receive services until the end of a school year even if they become stably housed at some point during the year.
